    "content": "## Basic\nTabs divide content into sections, allowing users to easily switch between them.\n<How isCenter={false} toUse=\"navigation/tabs/tabs-demo\" />\n\n## Installation\n<Installation options={{ isComponent: true }} items={['tabs']} />\n<WarningFramer/>\n\n## Manual Installation\n<Installation options={{ isManual: true }} items={['react-aria-components', 'motion']} />\n\n<SourceCode toShow='tabs' />\n\n## Anatomy\n<Anatomy show='tabs-anatomy'/>\n\n## With Icons\nIf you want to include icons in your tabs, it's simple to do. This tab setup handles icons smoothly, maintaining a clean design.\n<How isCenter={false} toUse=\"navigation/tabs/tabs-icons-demo\" />\n\n## Orientation\nYou can set the orientation of the tabs to either `horizontal` or `vertical`.\n<How isCenter={false} toUse=\"navigation/tabs/tabs-orientation-demo\" />\n\n## Collections\nTabs can also be used within collections.\n<How isCenter={false} toUse=\"navigation/tabs/tabs-collections-demo\" />\n\n## Links\nIf you want to use tabs as navigational links, you can add the `href` prop to the `Tab` component. This will automatically change the cursor to a pointer.\n<How isCenter={false} toUse=\"navigation/tabs/tabs-link-demo\" />\n\n## Responsive\nWhen tabs get crowded, they can become difficult to manage. To keep them organized and responsive, use the following approach:\n\n<Composed text=\"Mix it up with a menu, select, or combo box, but this example focuses on mastering the select component.\" components={['select']}/>\n\n<How isCenter={false} toUse=\"navigation/tabs/tabs-responsive-demo\" />\n\n## Disabled\nYou can disable all tabs by setting the `isDisabled` prop to `true`.\n<How isCenter={false} toUse=\"navigation/tabs/tabs-disabled-demo\" />\n\nYou can also disable individual tabs by setting the `isDisabled` prop for each one, like this:\n```tsx\n<Tab isDisabled id=\"c\">Contact</Tab>\n<Tab isDisabled id=\"a\">About Us</Tab>\n```",
